Lessons that can be learned from the Cuban Missile Crisis today
"Thirteen Days" ("Thirteen Days"), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, is due to open in cinemas in many countries soon.
Everyone should see this film, not just because it addresses the past, but also because it provides insights into current events – particularly with regard to the controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy convened his closest advisors in the White House.
Satellite images of the region revealed the construction of a nuclear weapons station on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and the decisions that one was unable to come to, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened during those days at the White House.
Audio recordings made during the presidency of Kennedy played a significant role in the creation of the film.
Following the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard launched a discussion round that should address the film and the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this round included, among others: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a professor of history at Harvard, who has written a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a professor of political science at Harvard, who presented a classical study on the Cuban crisis, the work "Essence of Decision", 30 years ago.
In addition, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the filmic treatment of the subject was criticized in various points, the discussion participants were able to agree that the film portrays the problems and the pressure with which President Kennedy was confronted exactly as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Missile Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized it as follows:
Advisors must play their role in the event of a crisis, but it is ultimately the President who must bear the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors - both civilian and military advisors - wanted to attack Cuba at the time.
Only through Kennedy's objective analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be shown to be significant in determining the consequences.
It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; in addition, communication channels must be kept open.
Driving a rival into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open that enable an understanding of the adversary's position could prove disastrous.
The US relies on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, further allies, as well as the world's opinion supported him.
· Time is needed for a meeting of good decisions.
When it comes down to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into a decision.
The fact that a week passed in which all involved factors were scrutinized and weighed to the finest detail was decisive for the result.
But would such a time frame for weighing options even exist today in light of the mass media that currently exist?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the position of the opponent.
In one of the scenes heavily criticized in the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade imposed by Kennedy over Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to President Khrushchev about Kennedy's intentions, rather than a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more laid-back?
In the end, the US had also deployed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba only reflected this policy.
However, Kennedy showed himself anxious regarding the consequences that would have been brought about by the stationing of Soviet missiles on Cuba with regard to Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, the Berlin Crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban Missile Crisis, according to the historian Ernest May.
"It will soon be too late," was a frequently cited argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba, even as they believed the missiles were heading towards Cuba by sea.
A U.S. force of around 180,000 men was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a lightning bombing raid, which would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack on Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," McNamara said, "to find out that there were already nuclear warheads on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those 90 were strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information on the occasion of a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
What would the consequences have been for Cuba?
I knew it.
And I have explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the extermination of Cuba.
Castro and - to a greater extent - his fellow comrade Che Guevara were prepared to let Cuba go up in smoke, so that their country would become a martyr in the fight for world revolution.
An invasion would have therefore potentially resulted in the deaths of 80 million US Americans and the destruction of Cuba, only because the Kennedy administration lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is firmly convinced that an invasion would "certainly" have led to a Soviet nuclear attack on the United States.
Nikita Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was in fact limited: U2 planes flying over Cuban airspace were fired upon, despite explicit instructions to the contrary from the Chairman.
A difficult question to answer, which did not come up during this debate at Harvard, is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who distinguished himself during the crisis by rational behavior, but rather an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
In light of the spread of atomic weapons, this threat could one day become reality.
Current discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear extortion by rogue states should be led in light of this horrific, yet entirely realistic thought.
Harvard has put a new web site online, where the key documents on the Cuban Missile Crisis, as well as on the current nuclear threats, can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
